Quick sort is a sorting algorithm that employs the "divide and conquer" technique. It works by selecting a 'pivot' element from the array and partitioning the other elements into two sub-arrays, based on whether they are less than or greater than the pivot. The sub-arrays are then recursively sorted.

Here is the Python implementation of the quick sort algorithm:

```python
def quickSort(arr):
  if len(arr) <= 1:
    return arr
  else:
    pivot = arr.pop()
    items_greater = []
    items_lower = []
    for item in arr:
        if item > pivot:
            items_greater.append(item)
        else:
            items_lower.append(item)
    return quickSort(items_lower) + [pivot] + quickSort(items_greater)

# Testing the quickSort function
print(quickSort([3, 6, 8, 10, 1, 2, 1]))
```

This script will output:
```[1, 1, 2, 3, 6, 8, 10]```

This implementation has an average and best case time complexity of O(n log n) where 'n' is the number of elements being sorted. The worst case time complexity is O(n^2). The worst case happens when the smallest or largest element is always chosen as the pivot. This Python script chose the last element as the pivot so it will end up with worst case time complexity when input list is already sorted in ascending or descending order.

