Here's a simple implementation using brute force method to solve your problem:

```java
import java.util.*;

public class Solution {
    public boolean fourElementsProductEqualsOne(List<Float> l) {
        int n = l.size();
        if(n < 4) return false;
        // Generate all possible combinations of four elements
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 3; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n - 2; j++) {
                for (int k = j + 1; k < n - 1; k++) {
                    for (int m = k + 1; m < n; m++) {
                        // Check if the product of elements is one
                        if (l.get(i) * l.get(j) * l.get(k) * l.get(m) == 1) {
                            return true;
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        // If no combination is found, return false
        return false;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Solution solution = new Solution();

        System.out.println(solution.fourElementsProductEqualsOne(Arrays.asList(1.0f, 0.5f, 2.0f, 1.0f))); // should print true
        System.out.println(solution.fourElementsProductEqualsOne(Arrays.asList(1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f, 7.0f))); // should print false
    }
}
```

This code works correctly, but notice that the time complexity is O(n^4) because of the four nested loops, where n is the size of the list. Depending on the size of the list, your program may take a long time to run.

Here's how you can do it in Java by creating a method to swap two numbers, without using a third variable.

``` java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 5;
        int b = 10;

        System.out.println("Before swapping, a is " + a + " and b is " + b);
        // calling the method
        swap(a, b);
    }

    // method to swap two numbers without using third variable
    public static void swap(int a, int b) {
        a = a + b;
        b = a - b;
        a = a - b;

        System.out.println("After swapping, a is " + a + " and b is " + b);
    }
}
```

This program will output:

Before swapping, a is 5 and b is 10  
After swapping, a is 10 and b is 5  

In this program, `swap()` method exchanges the positions of `a` and `b` without needing another variable. This is done by adding `a` and `b`, and storing the result in `a`. Then, subtract `b` from `a` and store the result in `b`. Then subtract `b` from `a` and again store the result back in `a`. These operations successfully swap `a` and `b`.

Here is one way to code this in C++. This version cyclically rotates the array to the right by a given number of positions.

```c++
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void circularShift(vector<int>& arr, int shift) {
    int n = arr.size();
    shift %= n;
    rotate(arr.begin(), arr.begin() + n - shift, arr.end());
}

void printArray(const vector<int>& arr) {
    for (int i : arr) cout << i << " ";
    cout << endl;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8};
    int shift = 10;  // You can change this to any positive number

    cout << "Original array: ";
    printArray(arr);

    circularShift(arr, shift);

    cout << "After shifting: ";
    printArray(arr);
    return 0;
}
```

In this C++ code, we are firstly taking an array vector with some elements and a shift amount as input.

`rotate()` function from STL is used for rotating the array. The function rotates elements such that the element at arr.begin()+n-shift becomes the new first element.

At last, we print the original array and the array after being shifted.

This program uses STL, which makes it more compact and more readable. It supports dynamic array sizes and accurately performs the shift operation even if the shift requirement is greater than the array size. If that's the case, the surplus shift over the array size will be performed which is achieved by taking shift modulo array size. 

This program shifts the array to the right, but you can easily modify it to shift the array to the left by switching n-shift to shift in the rotate() function.

